                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/>δοͱιτ ιμ Ρυκες ͱαζσυιε<supplied reason="lost">ς</supplied>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" subtype="transliteration" xml:lang="scx-Latn">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/>dohit im rukes hazsuie<supplied reason="lost">s</supplied>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app>
                        <note>Text after Manganaro 1961</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#VM">
                <p>Gives this Ruke Hazsuie / Gift of Ruke Hazsuie.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it" resp="#VM">
                <p>Dà questo Ruke Hazsuie / Dono di Ruke Hazsuie.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The inscription has been interpreted by all editors as  'gift of' + an onomastic formula. It is on a fragment of a tile found in 
                    contrada Mendolito together with another one apparently written by the same hand. The two documents were initially 
                    interpreted as two funerary inscriptions (Manganaro 1961b, 110), then as a single votive inscription dedicated by magistrates 
                    to deities (Pisani 1964, 127; Whatmough 1968, 576-577; Ribezzo 1923, 224) and, more recently (Cultraro 2005), as a single 
                    inscription on the roofing slabs of a building (a house, or more likely a 'public' building) that would bear the dedication of 
                    a member of the community financing the structure.
                    Whether these are parts of the same inscription is, however, difficult to prove due to the lack of specific details on the archaeological 
                    context and a connection - if not palaeographic - between this inscription and the other one that bears another (and different) onomastic 
                    formula (maybe the name of another donor). 
                    The alphabet is the typical one of Sikel inscriptions from the Etna area. Worthy of note, in particular, is the presence of the arrow-shaped alpha, the digamma 
                    (with value of v, see also <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic003364">ISic003364</ref>).</p>
            </div>
